aadd.example:
These examples show what happens when you invoke AAdd() more than once:

  LOCAL aArray AS ARRAY
  aArray := {}					// aArray is an empty array
  AAdd(aArray, 5)			// aArray is {5}
  AAdd(aArray, 10)			// aArray is {5, 10}
  AAdd(aArray, {12, 10})		// aArray is {5, 10, {12, 10}}

aclone.example:
This example creates an array, then duplicates it using AClone().  The first array is then altered, but the duplicate copy is unaffected:

  LOCAL aOne, aTwo AS ARRAY
  aOne := {1, 2, 3}			// aOne is {1, 2, 3}
  aTwo := AClone(aOne)			// aTwo is {1, 2, 3}
  aOne[1] := 99				// aOne is {99, 2, 3}
  						// but aTwo is still {1,2,3}

acloneshallow.example:
This example creates an array and duplicates it using ACloneShallow().  Moreover, by changing an element in the source subarray that automatically affects the target subarray, it  illustrates that subarrays are copied by reference:

  LOCAL aSource, aTarget, aSourceSubArray AS ARRAY
  aSourceSubArray := {3,4,5}
  aSource := {1, 2, aSourceSubArray}
  aTarget := ACloneShallow(aSource)
  // aTarget is {1, 2, {3,4,5}}
  // Now change the source subarray
  aSourceSubArray[3] := 100
  // The change is also reflected in aTarget
  // aTarget is {1, 2, {3,4,100}}

acopy.example:
This example creates two arrays, each filled with a value.  The first two elements from the source array are then copied into the target array:

  LOCAL nCount := 2, nStart := 1, aOne, aTwo
  aOne := {1, 1, 1}
  aTwo := {2, 2, 2}
  ACopy(aOne, aTwo, nStart, nCount)
  // aTwo is now {1, 1, 2}

This example copies an array in reverse order into another array:

  FUNCTION Start()
  	LOCAL a1, a2 AS ARRAY
  	a1 := {1, 2, 3, 4, 5}
  	a2: = ArrayCreate(ALen(a1))
  		// Start from end and step backwards
  	ACopy(a1, a2, -1, - 0xFFFF, 1)	// reverse array

adel.example:
This example creates an array of three elements, then deletes the second element.  The third element is moved up one position, and the new third element is assigned a NIL:

  LOCAL aArray
  aArray := {1, 2, 3}		// aArray is now {1, 2, 3}
  ADel(aArray, 2)			// aArray is now {1, 3, NIL}

afill.example:
This example creates a 3-element array.  The array is then filled with the logical value FALSE.  Finally, elements in positions 2 and 3 are assigned the new value TRUE:

  LOCAL aLogic[3]			// aLogic is {NIL, NIL, NIL}
  AFill(aLogic, FALSE)		// aLogic is {FALSE, FALSE, FALSE}
  AFill(aLogic, TRUE, 2, 2)		// aLogic is {FALSE, TRUE, TRUE}

This example fills up the individual rows of a multidimensional array:

  LOCAL a2[3][3]	//a 2-dimensional array
  AFill(a2[1], "One")
  AFill(a2[2], "Two")
  AFill(a2[3], "Three")

ains.example:
This example demonstrates the effect of using AIns() on an array:

  LOCAL aArray AS ARRAY
  aArray := {1, 2, 3}			// aArray is now {1, 2, 3}
  AIns(aArray, 2)			// aArray is now {1, NIL, 2}

arraybuild.example:
This example creates an empty array using the ArrayBuild() function, then shows the equivalent action by assigning a literal array:

  aArray := ArrayBuild()
  aArray := {}

arraynew.example:
This example creates a one-dimensional array of five elements using the ArrayNew() function, then shows the equivalent action by assigning a literal array of NIL values:

  LOCAL aArray AS ARRAY
  aArray := ArrayNew(5)
  aArray := {NIL, NIL, NIL, NIL, NIL}

This example shows three different statements which create the same multidimensional array:

  aArray := ArrayNew(3, 2)
  aArray := {{NIL, NIL}, {NIL, NIL}, {NIL, NIL}}
  aArray := {ArrayCreate(2), ArrayCreate(2), ArrayCreate(2)}

This example creates a multidimensional array:
aArray := ArrayNew(3, 2, 5)

asend.example:
This example sends a simple message to an array of objects for evaluation.  Each elemental object evaluates the message in turn:

  CLASS Greet
  METHOD Salut(cRest) CLASS Greet
  	? Hello", cRest
  	RETURN
  FUNCTION Start()
  	LOCAL oAlpha, oBeta, oGamma, oDelta, oEpsilon ;
  		AS OBJECT
  	LOCAL aBunch AS ARRAY
  	oAlpha   := Greet{}
  	oBeta    := Greet{}
  	oGamma    := Greet{}
  	oDelta   := Greet{}
  	oEpsilon := Greet{}
  	aBunch := {oAlpha, oBeta, oGamma, oDelta, oEpsilon}
  	ASend(aBunch, #Salut, "world")
  	// Equivalent output
  	AEval(aBunch, {|aTemp| aTemp:Salut("world")})

asendclass.example:
This example sends a simple message to an array of objects for evaluation.  Each elemental object evaluates the message in turn:

  CLASS Greet
  METHOD Salut(cRest) CLASS Greet
  	? "Hello", cRest
  	RETURN
  FUNCTION Start()
  	LOCAL oAlpha, oBeta, oGamma, oDelta, oEpsilon ;
  		AS OBJECT
  	LOCAL aBunch AS ARRAY
  	oAlpha   := Greet{}
  	oBeta    := Greet{}
  	oGamma    := Greet{}
  	oDelta   := Greet{}
  	oEpsilon := Greet{}
  	aBunch := {oAlpha, oBeta, oGamma, oDelta, oEpsilon}
  	ASendClass(aBunch, #Salut, #Greet, "world")
  	// Equivalent output
  	AEval(aBunch, {|aTemp| aTemp:Salut("world")})

asize.example:
These examples demonstrate adding new elements and deleting existing elements:

  LOCAL aArray AS ARRAY
  aArray := {1}			// aArray is {1}
