vodbeval.example:
This example uses VODBEval() to implement Count(), a function that counts the number of records in a work area matching a specified scope.  The scope is passed as an array to Count().  A set of constants defines the elements of the scope array:

  // Scope attribute constants
  DEFINE FOR_COND		:=	1	AS SHORTINT
  DEFINE WHILE_COND		:=	2	AS SHORTINT
  DEFINE NEXT_SCOPE		:=	3	AS SHORTINT
  DEFINE REC_SCOPE		:=	4	AS SHORTINT
  DEFINE REST_SCOPE		:=	5	AS SHORTINT
  DEFINE SCOPE_ELEMENTS	:=	5	AS SHORTINT
  FUNCTION Start()
  	// Create a scope and count records using it
  	LOCAL mySet[SCOPE_ELEMENTS]
  	LOCAL myCount AS LONGINT
  	USE customer NEW
  	mySet[FOR_COND] := {||customer = "Smith"}
  	mySet[WHILE_COND] := {||zip > "90000"}
  	mySet[REST_SCOPE] := FALSE
  	// Every record (ALL)
  	myCount := Count(mySet)
  	RETURN TRUE
  FUNCTION Count(aScope) AS LONGINT
  	LOCAL nCount := 0 AS LONGINT
  	VODBEval({|| nCount++},;
  		aScope[FOR_COND],;
  		aScope[WHILE_COND],;
  		aScope[NEXT_SCOPE],;
  		aScope[REC_SCOPE],;
  		aScope[REST_SCOPE])
  	RETURN nCount

_getinst.example:
The following example loads a string from the string table. This example requires the Win32 API library to be included in the application's search path:
FUNCTION Start() LOCAL x := BUFFER(64) AS STRING LOCAL cb AS WORD cb := LoadString(_GetInst(), 100, x, 64) x := LEFT(x, cb) ? x // Hello World
RESOURCE StringTable { 100, "Hello World" }
